<tr><td>Google Play Books</td><td>52-70%</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td>3B Android devices</td><td>Global mobile readers</td></tr>
<tr><td>Apple Books</td><td>70%</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td>iOS/Mac users</td><td>Premium/literary authors</td></tr>
<tr><td>Draft2Digital</td><td>~63% (after fees)</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td>10+ stores</td><td>Wide distribution, minimal effort</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gumroad/Payhip</td><td>~95% (after fees)</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td>Your own audience</td><td>Established authors with following</td></tr>
<tr><td>Amazon KDP</td><td>35-70%</td><td>KDP Select requires it</td><td>No (MOBI/AZW3)</td><td>Largest single store</td><td>If you must stay on Amazon</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr />

<h2 id="how-to-migrate">How to Migrate Your Existing Amazon Books to EPUB</h2>
<p>If you have books on Amazon and want to publish them on other platforms, here is the practical workflow:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Export your source files.</strong> If you still have the original DOCX, Markdown, or InDesign files, use those. They are DRM-free and you own them fully.</li>
<li><strong>Convert to EPUB.</strong> Use <a href="/">converter-epub.com</a> to convert DOCX or HTML to EPUB, or use <a href="/blog/calibre-vs-sigil-2026/">Calibre or Sigil</a> for batch conversion.</li>
<li><strong>Validate the EPUB.</strong> Run the file through <a href="https://validator.w3.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">W3C EPUB Validator</a> (free, online) to check for formatting errors.</li>
<li><strong>Create store accounts.</strong> Sign up for Kobo Writing Life, Google Play Books Partner Center, and/or Draft2Digital. Each requires tax information and payment details.</li>
<li><strong>Upload and set pricing.</strong> Set your list price on each platform. There is no rule that prices must match across stores, though readers appreciate consistency.</li>
<li><strong>Update your author website.</strong> Add direct buy links for each platform. Use tools like Books2Read to generate a universal buy link that sends readers to their preferred store.</li>
</ol>
<p>If you no longer have your source files, you can <a href="/blog/kindle-to-epub/">convert Kindle books to EPUB</a> using Calibre with the DeDRM plugin — but check the legal status in your jurisdiction. The safest path is always using your original source files.</p>
<hr />

<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Can I keep my Amazon KDP account while publishing on Kobo?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Yes, as long as you do not enroll the book in KDP Select (Kindle Unlimited). KDP Select requires exclusivity. If you publish the book only on KDP standard plan (not Select), you are free to publish the same EPUB on Kobo, Apple Books, Google Play, and anywhere else.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Do I need to reformat my book for each platform?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Most platforms accept a standard EPUB 3 file. Kobo, Google Play Books, and Apple Books all take EPUB directly. Draft2Digital may ask for EPUB or DOCX. You should keep a clean EPUB 3 master file and use platform-specific preview tools to check how it renders before publishing.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">What happens to my Amazon rankings if I leave?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Your existing Amazon rankings remain if you keep the book on KDP standard plan (non-Select). You lose the Kindle Unlimited page-read royalties and the visibility boost that comes with Select exclusivity. Many authors find the trade-off worthwhile because the combined audience of Kobo + Apple Books + Google Play exceeds Kindle Unlimited readership for most non-romance genres.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Is EPUB better than MOBI for self-publishing?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Yes. EPUB is the international standard ebook format (ISO 24611:2026). Amazon originally used MOBI, then moved to AZW3, and now supports KPF (Kindle Package Format). EPUB works on every non-Amazon device and is the required format for Apple Books, Google Play, Kobo, and library lending through OverDrive. See our <a href="/blog/epub-vs-pdf-vs-mobi-vs-azw3/">EPUB vs PDF vs MOBI vs AZW3 comparison</a> for details.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">Can I sell EPUB directly to readers without a middleman?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Absolutely. Gumroad, Payhip, and SendOwl all support EPUB delivery. You keep 90-97% of the sale price after payment processing. The trade-off is that you handle your own marketing, customer support, and file hosting. Many established authors use a hybrid model: direct sales on Gumroad for their superfans plus Draft2Digital for library and store distribution.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

